Lab Manual: Hash Table Using Chaining with User Input in C
Practical Title
Implement a Hash Table of size 10 using division method as hash function and chaining for collision resolution. Perform Insert, Search, and Delete operations using user input.
Objective
To implement a hash table using:
- Division method (`key % 10`) as the hash function
- Chaining for collision handling (using linked lists)
- User-driven interface for inserting, searching, deleting and displaying key-value pairs
Theory
Hash Table
A hash table is a data structure that stores key-value pairs and uses a hash function to compute an index into an array of buckets or slots from which the desired value can be found.
Hash Function (Division Method)
The division method is one of the simplest hash functions, defined as:
hash(key) = key % table_size
In this practical, the table_size = 10, so:
index = key % 10
Collision
A collision occurs when two keys hash to the same index. We resolve this using:
Chaining
Chaining handles collisions by maintaining a linked list at each hash index. Multiple entries are chained together at the same location.
Software & Hardware Requirements
Software	Version
GCC Compiler	Any
OS	Windows/Linux
Text Editor	Code::Blocks / Dev-C++ / VS Code

Hardware	Specification
Processor	1 GHz or faster
RAM	512 MB or more
Algorithm
1. Insert(key, value):
   - Compute index using key % 10
   - Create a new node and insert at the head of the linked list at that index

2. Search(key):
   - Compute index using key % 10
   - Traverse the linked list at that index to find the key

3. Delete(key):
   - Compute index using key % 10
   - Traverse the linked list to locate and remove the node with the given key

4. Display:
   - For each index, display the list of key-value pairs in that chain
C Program: Hash Table with Chaining (User Input)

#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

#define TABLE_SIZE 10

struct Node {
    int key;
    char value[100];
    struct Node* next;
};

struct Node* hashTable[TABLE_SIZE];

int hashFunction(int key) {
    return key % TABLE_SIZE;
}

void insert(int key, char* value) {
    int index = hashFunction(key);
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->key = key;
    strcpy(newNode->value, value);
    newNode->next = hashTable[index];
    hashTable[index] = newNode;
    printf("Inserted (%d, %s) at index %d\n", key, value, index);
}

void search(int key) {
    int index = hashFunction(key);
    struct Node* temp = hashTable[index];
    while (temp != NULL) {
        if (temp->key == key) {
            printf("Key %d found with value: %s\n", key, temp->value);
            return;
        }
        temp = temp->next;
    }
    printf("Key %d not found\n", key);
}

void delete(int key) {
    int index = hashFunction(key);
    struct Node* temp = hashTable[index];
    struct Node* prev = NULL;

    while (temp != NULL) {
        if (temp->key == key) {
            if (prev == NULL)
                hashTable[index] = temp->next;
            else
                prev->next = temp->next;
            free(temp);
            printf("Key %d deleted successfully\n", key);
            return;
        }
        prev = temp;
        temp = temp->next;
    }
    printf("Key %d not found for deletion\n", key);
}

void display() {
    printf("\nHash Table:\n");
    for (int i = 0; i < TABLE_SIZE; i++) {
        struct Node* temp = hashTable[i];
        printf("[%d]: ", i);
        while (temp != NULL) {
            printf("(%d, %s) -> ", temp->key, temp->value);
            temp = temp->next;
        }
        printf("NULL\n");
    }
}

int main() {
    int choice, key;
    char value[100];

    while (1) {
        printf("\n---- Hash Table Operations ----\n");
        printf("1. Insert\n");
        printf("2. Search\n");
        printf("3. Delete\n");
        printf("4. Display\n");
        printf("5. Exit\n");
        printf("Enter your choice: ");
        scanf("%d", &choice);

        switch (choice) {
            case 1:
                printf("Enter key (integer): ");
                scanf("%d", &key);
                printf("Enter value (string): ");
                scanf("%s", value);
                insert(key, value);
                break;
            case 2:
                printf("Enter key to search: ");
                scanf("%d", &key);
                search(key);
                break;
            case 3:
                printf("Enter key to delete: ");
                scanf("%d", &key);
                delete(key);
                break;
            case 4:
                display();
                break;
            case 5:
                printf("Exiting program.\n");
                exit(0);
            default:
                printf("Invalid choice! Please try again.\n");
        }
    }
    return 0;
}

Conclusion
Hash tables offer fast access using keys.
The division method provides a simple and efficient hash function.
Chaining handles collisions effectively using linked lists.
The implemented program provides flexibility to insert, search, and delete dynamically using user input.
